<br>
You conspicuously avoided addressing the fact that Hussein has been committing genocide on a regular basis for decades.  Civil disobedience is a very noble concept, but once again you're projecting your own values onto a completely disparate culture.  Try non-aggressive disobedience in pre-war Iraq and you'd have found yourself on the business end of a cattle prod while your feet were in a bucket of water.  You're still laboring under the ideological illusion that Hussein and his ilk play by the same rules as the rest of us.  They don't.<br>
<br>
The Middle East (particularly Iraq/Iran/Syria) is not Europe.  You can embrace the philosophies of Gandhi and Martin Luther King right up until the point when the secret police kick in your door and drag you out with a black bag over your head.  <br>
<br>
How were the Iraqi people to find their own solution?  The same way the Russians did under Stalin?  The comparison is dead-on.  How do you rise against a regime that punishes even the most moderate protests with torture and death?  How can you speak out, let alone enact armed rebellion, against a government that murders your wife and children in front of you before killing you?  <br>
<br>
The rest of the world turns a blind eye to regimes like this and pretends that they don't exist.  America is as guilty of this as anyone.  Ask the 900+ residents of the Congo who were massacred this weekend how they feel about the UN's diplomatic efforts to enact a regime change there.  Ask them how they feel about the peace process.  Ask the 3,000 victims of the WTC bombing how effective they think diplomacy was in dealing with Afghanistan.  Ask the thousands of one-armed children in Sierra Leone who are the victims of government (and rebel) mutilation squads how happy they are for the peaceful resolutions being pursued for their country.  Ask the residents of the mass graves in Srebrenica and Rwanda.  Think about this tonight while you're playing Everquest:  <br>
<br>
Evil triumphs when good men do nothing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chrispycj8>ChrisPycj8</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Qeynos Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#628CBC>(4/7/03 1:48:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=548.topic&index=87>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .</span><hr size=1> &quot;Why do you state that the majority of the people in Iraq wants Sadam removed from power? Does that mean that America have the right to start a war?&quot;<br>
